ngland":"Skipton, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pichard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire) and German: habitational name for someone from Picardy in northern France (see   Picard   1).","English: in some cases, possibly also from the Old French personal name <i>Picard</i>, probably from an ancient Germanic name, composed of the elements <i>bic</i> ‘sharp point, pointed weapon’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’."],"variants":[{"name":"Picard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Lucien, Andre, Marcel, Emile, Michel, Normand, Adrien, Antoine, Benoit, Elzear, Fernand.","French, Walloon, Catalan, and German; Breton (also <b>Le Picard</b>): from Old French and Catalan <i>picard</i> ‘Picard’, a habitational name for someone from Picardy in northern France. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium. Compare   Pecore  .","French: in some cases, probably also from <i>pic</i> ‘pick, pike’ + the pejorative suffix <i>-ard</i>, applied as a nickname for e.g. a user of a pointed tool."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":0,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":20,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":30,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":40,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Nicholas Pichard was born in 1066, in Skipton, Yorkshire, England, his father, Nicholas de Picard, was 36 and his mother, Mrs. Nicholas de Picard, was 30. He married Mrs. Nicholas Pickard after 1066, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1160, in Runcorn, Cheshire, England, at the age of 94, and was buried in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1066–1160":"1066–1160","1069–Female":"1069–Surnud","1066–Female":"1066–Surnud","1106–1134":"1106–1134","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","1036–Female":"1036–Surnud","AFT 1066":"pärast 1066","1106":"1106","1036":"1036","1069":"1069","Aft 1134":"pärast 1134","1134":"1134","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1030":"1030","1160":"1160","Dutton, Cheshire, England":"Dutton, Cheshire, England","Keckwick, Cheshire, England":"Keckwick, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, England",", , , England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Skipton-in-Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Skipton, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1066–1160":"1066–1160","1069–Female":"1069–Kuollut","1066–Female":"1066–Kuollut","1106–1134":"1106–1134","1030–Male":"1030–Kuollut","1036–Female":"1036–Kuollut","AFT 1066":"1066 jälkeen","1106":"1106","1036":"1036","1069":"1069","Aft 1134":"1134 jälkeen","1134":"1134","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1030":"1030","1160":"1160","Dutton, Cheshire, England":"Dutton, Cheshire, England","Keckwick, Cheshire, England":"Keckwick, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, England",", , , England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Skipton-in-Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Skipton, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1066–1160":"1066–1160","1069–Female":"1069–Décédée","1066–Female":"1066–Décédée","1106–1134":"1106–1134","1030–Male":"1030–Décédé","1036–Female":"1036–Dé